### 3. Types of Critical Points for 2d Systems

We can use the eigenvalues and eigenvectors to anticipate what solutions around $\underline{critical points}$ (y' = 0, steady states) look like. This will be really useful for controls!

If the eigenvalues are $\underline{real}$ and distinct:

\begin{align}
\begin{equation}
\lambda_1 > \lambda_2 > 0
\end{equation}

improper node (unstable)

\begin{equation}
\lambda_1 < \lambda_2 < 0
\end{equation}

improper node (stable)

\begin{equation}
\lambda_1 > 0, & \lambda_2 < 0
\end{equation}

saddle
\end{align}

If the eigenvalues are $\underline{complex}$ & \lambda = \alpha \pm  \omega i:

\begin{align}
\begin{equation}
\alpha > 0
\end{equation}

spiral (unstable)

\begin{equation}
\alpha < 0
\end{equation}

spiral (stable)

\begin{equation}
\alpha = 0
\end{equation}

center
\end{align}

The direction depends on the matrix and can be checked for some point (e.g. (1,0)).
\begin{align}
If \vv{A} = 
&
\begin{bmatrix}
-7 & 2 & -3 \\
2 & -4 & -6 \\
-1 & -2 & -3
\end{bmatrix} & ,
\end{align}

b-c>0 & \to & clockwise

b-c<0 & \to & counterclockwise

If the eigenvalues are $\underline{real}$ and $\underline{repeated}$ & (\lambda_1 = \lambda_2):

\begin{align}
\vv{A} is a multiple of \vv{I}

proper node/star

direction depends on \vv{A} as for complex

degenerate node

unstable vs. stable

\begin{equation}
\lambda > 0 & \lambda < 0
\end{equation}
\end{align}


